FG-281 — AR “What We Asked / What They Answered” Card
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Turn comments into a response scorecard—the silence is your remedy.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: One page, four rows: Topic • Comment pin • Decision page • Response? Highlight “No response.” Pair with a reasoned-response remand ask.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 4-row card and mark one “No response” line.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Vendor timing — AR 118:12 — Decision p.7 — No response → remand 30d for response.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Silence, mapped, becomes an order.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A table with one row shaded red: “No response.”

⸻

FG-282 — Petition “Two-Page Mini-Reply” (Fit Only)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A tight 2-page reply fixes fit errors; nothing else.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Structure: (1) Misfit statement (≤2 lines); (2) Two pins; (3) One-line relief; no new facts; hash if posted.
	•	📝 Assignment: Convert a 6-page reply draft into 2 pages with the structure above.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Agency ignores timing harms (AR 118:12); reasoned-response duty unmet → remand 30d.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Fit cures more than flourish.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A long draft shrinking to a crisp two-page card.

⸻

FG-283 — Plain-Error Rescue (Preserve Forfeiture, Not Waiver)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: If an issue wasn’t preserved, argue forfeiture + plain error, not waiver.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Four prongs: error • plain • affects rights • seriously affects fairness; tie each to one pin; keep remedy narrow.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 7-line plain-error paragraph with two pins.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Error—wrong test; plain—settled law; harm—skipped factor (Dkt 18:2); fairness—urgent timing; remedy—remand 21d.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Rescue lanes exist—use them precisely.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A four-step ladder labeled Error/Plain/Rights/Fairness.

⸻

FG-284 — Petition 10/10/7 Schedule Note (Check One)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Offer the court a ready schedule with a check box.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Footer menu: “□ 10/10/7 (O/R/Rep)   □ 7/7/3 (O/R/Rep)”; show trigger math in a small table; neutral tone.
	•	📝 Assignment: Paste a two-option schedule at the end of your motion.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Trigger FR 08/01 → due 09/30; □ 10/10/7 or □ 7/7/3; order attached.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Schedules win when they’re selectable.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two checkboxes beside a tiny date table.

⸻

FG-285 — Agency Data Exhibit (Methods Note + View Copy)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Pair a methods note with a view copy—trust before charts.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Methods note (source, capture, transform, hash); view copy (printable table); native lodged under seal if needed; cite methods first.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 6-line methods note for one data exhibit.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Data from FR 88:12345 (captured 08/19); parsed to table; SHA-256 …; native CSV lodged.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Provenance makes numbers legal.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small “Methods” card pointing to a clean table.

⸻

FG-286 — Intervenor OA Time (Distinct Topic, 3–5 Minutes)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Intervenors win time by adding non-duplicative value.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: One issue; 3–5 minutes; coordination note; return time if duplicative; attach a time-split order.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 6-line intervenor OA request on one discrete topic.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Relief: 5 min for timing-harms data; coordination confirmed; no duplication; order attached.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Small, distinct asks get granted.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A tiny mic with “5:00” and a one-topic tag.

⸻

FG-287 — Petition “Clarify or Hold” After Opinion
	•	⚖️ Core Message: If opinion misreads or a related case is pending, ask to clarify or hold—briefly.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: (1) Quote the line; (2) Pin the record; (3) Clarify one sentence or hold pending case with date; no new facts.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 7-line clarify/hold motion.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Clarify ‘reached harm’ → ‘not reached’ (AR/Dkt pin) or hold 21d pending [case].”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Fix lens or wait for the binding answer.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A pencil icon and a small pause badge on one card.

⸻

FG-288 — Petition Addendum Hygiene (Texts Only, Hash Footer)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Only texts belong in addendum—rules, statutes, and official excerpts.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: No facts or screenshots; add source notes + captured; SHA-256 at footer if hosted; evidence pages stay in appendix.
	•	📝 Assignment: Move two non-text pages from your addendum to the appendix; add hash footers.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Add. Tab A—Rule __ (captured 08/19; SHA-256 9f2a…); evidence moved to Appx Tab 3.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Clean lanes make clean decisions.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two shelves: “Texts” (addendum) and “Proof” (appendix).

⸻

FG-289 — Consolidated Caption & Service (Multiple Petitions)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Unify captions and service lists across numbers.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Use a lead caption; file a unified Rule 26.1/7.1 disclosure; attach consolidated service list; submit an ECF metadata notice if inconsistent.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 7-line consolidation/metadata notice with an updated service list.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Lead caption: D.C. Cir. No. __; consolidated service attached; correct counsel email to x@y; no schedule impact.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: One caption = one story.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Three case tiles collapsing into one header bar.

⸻

FG-290 — Petition “One-Screen” OA Card (Q • Std • Pins • Relief)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Your OA kit should fit on one screen.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Question (≤12 words), Standard (one cite), Two pins (AR/Dkt), Relief (two lines). Hash and label; file same-day notice if allowed.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build the one-screen OA card for your petition.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Q: Must agency address timing comment? Std: arbitrary-and-capricious; Pins: AR 118:12; FR 88:12345; Relief: remand 30d for reasoned response.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Small screen, big leverage.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A phone-sized card with four tight blocks and a fingerprint footer.